        "other_parliamentary_business": [
            {
                "body": "The Pet Abduction Bill was approved by MPs in the House of Commons on Friday 19 April. It will now go to the House of Lords who also have to agree to it before it becomes law. \nWatch the debate (https://parliamentlive.tv/Event/Index/341f913f-aa07-473d-99f7-083205d99350)\nRead the transcript of the debate (https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2024-04-19/debates/0DFCB30F-AA26-4AE7-9D44-23602D85C77E/PetAbductionBill)\nWhat will the bill do?\nThe Bill would make dog and cat theft a specific criminal offence in England and Northern Ireland. People found guilty of the offence could be given up to five years in prison, a fine, or both.\nYou can read more about what the Bill would do in this House of Commons Library Research Briefing (https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-9929/).\nWhat happens next?\nHaving passed the House of Commons it will now go to the House of Lords. If the House of Lords make any changes to it, it will go back to the House of Commons who will decide if they agree with the changes. \nWhen both Houses agree the final text of the Bill, it will go to the King to receive Royal Assent. This means it becomes a law and is called an 'Act'. \nRead more about the bill and keep up to date with its progress (https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3549)\nRead more about how laws are made (https://www.parliament.uk/about/how/laws/passage-bill/)\nEasy Read: How laws are made (https://assets-learning.parliament.uk/uploads/2021/11/How-laws-are-made.pdf)\nGet involved in the work of the UK Parliament\nSign up to the UK Parliament newsletter (https://parliament.us14.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=098af33234df9814f59fb205f&id=6e29cb1262) for the latest information on how to get involved and make a difference.\n",
